TYPE: Observe,
TARGET: control modules 1-8 internal wiring and module orientation,
DESCRIPTION: Open the inspection panels of control modules 1–8 and visually inspect the internal connections and cable routing. For each module, determine which two terminals are tied to the internal switch/indicator circuit (the series path that opens/closes the 12 V line) and which two are simply the return/0 V line. Without unplugging anything, check whether any module is physically installed backwards in the chain (its intended 12 V ‘input’ pair actually connected toward the load, and its ‘output’ pair connected toward the supply). Record for each module whether its orientation and internal wiring match the intended series schematic.,
RESULT: Control Cubes 1–5 and 7–8 are oriented consistently in the chain: each switch connects between its module’s Control Input Cable (+) and Control Output Cable (+), with the (−) cables passed straight through, and there are no POLARITY INVERSIONs reported. For Cube 6, the internal positive-path connection is open: Control Switch 6 is only connected to Control Output Cable (+) 6, and Control Input Cable (+) 6 has a floating/disconnected end at its switch side. All green power-flow indicators and their resistors for modules 1–8 are physically absent and not replaceable.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-16 12:24:28 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 6'] hypothesis_explanation='Inspection shows that in Control Module 6 the positive path is not continuous: the switch/indicator circuit is only connected to the module’s positive OUTPUT cable, while the positive INPUT cable end is floating and not tied into the switch path. This means the series 12 V line from the power supply cannot reach downstream modules or the load; the circuit is open at Module 6 regardless of switch position. All other modules are oriented and wired correctly. Therefore Control Module 6 is the faulty component (internal open circuit in its positive-line wiring) and must be repaired or replaced to restore continuity and allow the lamp to turn on.'
