2026-04-16 12:25:27 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['cable connection between Control Module 5 and Control Module 6 (positive conductor)', 'cable connection between Control Module 6 and Control Module 7 (positive conductor)', 'internal positive-series conductor/terminal interface of Control Module 6'] hypothesis_explanation='When Control Module 6’s positive input and output conductors were hard‑jumpered together internally, the lamp turned ON, proving that: (1) the downstream chain from the CM6 positive output through CM7, CM8, and the load is intact; and (2) the upstream supply from the power module through CM5 up to the CM6 positive input is intact. In the normal (unjumpered) configuration, the lamp is OFF even with all switches ON, so the only way the jumper can restore operation is by bypassing an open in the CM6 series positive path or its immediate terminations.\n\nWe already know from inspection that CM6 is oriented correctly with no polarity inversion, and that its switch is connected only to the positive output cable while the positive input side appears floating. The prior replacement of CM6 as a whole was reported to have "no effect"; this suggests the cube itself is good, but the open persists in the wiring to, or from, the cube. Therefore the most probable fault is an open or mis‑termination in the positive series conductor at the interfaces involving CM6: either the cable/terminal carrying + between CM5→CM6, between CM6→CM7, or the way this conductor is landed on the internal positive input/output terminals of CM6. A configuration error (wrong plug pairing or one conductor not actually connected in the fast connector) could produce exactly the observed behavior while still allowing the temporary local jumper at CM6 to complete a path that dodges the miswired/open segment.\n\nThus I hypothesize a wiring/configuration fault involving the positive-series conductor at CM6 and its adjacent cable connections, not a failure of the internal electronics themselves. Repair should focus on correcting and securing the +12 V series conductor routing at these interfaces.'
